1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,544
This is Patch the Web from the very beginning, in one uninterrupted browser recording.

2
00:00:05,544 --> 00:00:12,507
Patch the Web lets people repair websites they do not own, then share that repair safely with everyone else.

3
00:00:12,518 --> 00:00:17,095
First, download the extension from the public Patch the Web site.

4
00:00:17,095 --> 00:00:22,869
Unzip it, open Chrome extensions, enable Developer mode, and choose Load unpacked.

5
00:00:22,869 --> 00:00:29,910
This clean demo profile now shows the real Patch the Web version zero point eight extension running.

6
00:00:29,917 --> 00:00:32,643
Now we open the MetroCare directory.

7
00:00:32,643 --> 00:00:39,231
The original website has twelve services, but no search, no filters, and no comparison.

8
00:00:39,231 --> 00:00:44,834
A person has to read every card to find accessible care in their language.

9
00:00:44,842 --> 00:00:47,780
We open the actual extension on this website.

10
00:00:47,780 --> 00:00:54,960
Patch the Web checks the public registry and discovers a community repair made for this exact domain and path.

11
00:00:54,960 --> 00:01:02,533
It verifies the publisher policy, the patch hash, and all eleven live selector targets before offering installation.

12
00:01:02,538 --> 00:01:06,320
One click installs and activates the verified feature.

13
00:01:06,320 --> 00:01:11,292
This is a constrained Patch the Web document, not arbitrary JavaScript.

14
00:01:11,292 --> 00:01:17,665
It may use only declared operations, and it receives access only to the website it repairs.

15
00:01:41,750 --> 00:01:46,041
The page reloads with the missing feature added by the extension.

16
00:01:46,041 --> 00:01:51,059
We select two real listings and open the new keyboard-accessible comparison.

17
00:01:51,059 --> 00:01:57,001
The original website remains intact; Patch the Web adds a personal usability layer on top.

18
00:01:57,003 --> 00:02:02,526
Next we filter for wheelchair access, Urdu, and providers accepting new patients.

19
00:02:02,526 --> 00:02:05,117
Twelve cards become one useful result.

20
00:02:05,117 --> 00:02:12,959
The filtering happens locally in the browser, so private preferences are not sent to MetroCare or to Patch the Web.

21
00:02:12,962 --> 00:02:14,434
We reload the website.

22
00:02:14,434 --> 00:02:20,858
The installed repair runs again automatically, and the unfinished filter choices are still here.

23
00:02:20,858 --> 00:02:27,349
This proves that the result is a working browser feature, not a screenshot or a one-time preview.

24
00:02:27,353 --> 00:02:36,548
Opening the extension again shows that the repair is active only on this website, every operation is healthy, and the permissions are reviewable.

25
00:02:36,548 --> 00:02:39,465
The user can disable or remove it at any time.

26
00:02:39,468 --> 00:02:48,719
GPT-5.6 through Codex helped design and threat-model the DSL, then authors new repairs from DOM and screenshot evidence.

27
00:02:48,719 --> 00:02:54,269
Everyone else installs the result without AI, an account, or an API key.

28
00:02:54,269 --> 00:02:55,965
That is Patch the Web.
